<div id="review_1602519784" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1602519784" />
    <a title="Don" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/750659-don"><img alt="Don" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1404913662p2/750659.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1602519784?book_show_action=true">Jun 11, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Don" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Don" href="/user/show/750659-don">Don</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/750659-don?shelf=philosophy-religion">philosophy-religion</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1602519784" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15698387248834108905">The book addresses three primary questions or inquiries - (1) is religion necessary; (2) does God exist; and (3) is it possible to have an atheistic spirituality. While the answers to these questions may be assumed (based on the title of the book), what sets this apart from so many other works discussing the philosophy of religion and atheism is its tone. Comte-Sponville&apos;s words radiate not only intelligence and deep contemplation, but compassion, sincerity, and universal respect. The book is wo</span>
  <span id="freeText15698387248834108905" style="display:none">The book addresses three primary questions or inquiries - (1) is religion necessary; (2) does God exist; and (3) is it possible to have an atheistic spirituality. While the answers to these questions may be assumed (based on the title of the book), what sets this apart from so many other works discussing the philosophy of religion and atheism is its tone. Comte-Sponville's words radiate not only intelligence and deep contemplation, but compassion, sincerity, and universal respect. The book is worth reading from that standpoint alone, in my opinion, as it can serve as an example of how to discuss and think about complicated and meaningful ideas in a way that preserve the respect of freedom of thought and its necessary diversity. Personally, the book was powerful in many ways, and will be one that I imagine I will revisit from time to time.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15698387248834108905" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


